column5: 1. How much were you able to control events?
column6: 2. How responsive was the environment to actions that you initiated (or performed)?
column7: 3. How natural did your interactions with the environment seem?
column8: 4. How much did the visual aspects of the environment involve you?
column9: 5. How much did the auditory aspects of the environment involve you?
column10: 6. How natural was the mechanism which controlled movement through the environment?
column11: 7. How compelling was your sense of objects moving through space?
column12: 8. How much did your experiences in the virtual environment seem consistent with your real-world experiences?
column13: 9. Were you able to anticipate what would happen next in response to the actions that you performed?
column14: 10. How completely were you able to actively survey or search the environment using vision?
column15: 11. How well could you identify sounds?
column16: 12. How well could you localize sounds?
column17: 13. How well could you actively survey or search the virtual environment using touch?
column18: 14. How compelling was your sense of moving around inside the virtual environment?
column19: 15. How closely were you able to examine objects?
column20: 16. How well could you examine objects from multiple viewpoints?
column21: 17. How well could you move or manipulate objects in the virtual environment?
column22: 18. How involved were you in the virtual environment experience?
column23: 19. How much delay did you experience between your actions and expected outcomes?
column24: 20. How quickly did you adjust to the virtual environment experience?
column25: 21. How proficient in moving and interacting with the virtual environment did you feel at the end of the experience?
column26: 22. How much did the visual display quality interfere or distract you from performing assigned tasks or required activities?
column27: 23. How much did the control devices interfere with the performance of assigned tasks or with other activities?
column28: 24. How well could you concentrate on the assigned tasks or required activities rather than on the mechanisms used to perform those tasks or activities?
column29: 25. How completely were your senses engaged in this experience?
column30: 26. To what extent did events occurring outside the virtual environment distract from your experience in the virtual environment?
column31: 27. Overall, how much did you focus on using the display and control devices instead of the virtual experience and experimental tasks?
column32: 28. Were you involved in the experimental task to the extent that you lost track of time?
column33: 29. How easy was it to identify objects through physical interaction; like touching an object, walking over a surface, or bumping into a wall or object?
column34: 30. Were there moments during the virtual environment experience when you felt completely focused on the task or environment?
column35: 31. How easily did you adjust to the control devices used to interact with the virtual environment?
column36: 32. Was the information provided through different senses in the virtual environment (e.g., vision, hearing, touch) consistent?
